Treated as polytypic contra Marchant and Higgins (1993), Dickinson and Remsen (2013) and del Hoyo et al. (2014). Treatment based on morphological differences between eastern and western populations (Bennett 2010; Marchant and Higgins 1993), significant ecological differences and demographic isolation across a well known ultrataxon geographic barrier - the Nullabour coast (Schodde and Mason 1999). Preliminary analysis also suggests significant genetic differentiation between eastern mainland and western mainland populations (Bennett 2010).

column8: Subspecies from Schodde and Mason (1999). Meliphaga albilineata (Sibley and Monroe 1990, 1993; Christidis and Boles 1994) was split into M. albilineata and M. fordiana by Christidis and Boles (2008) but this treatment is not followed because BirdLife International does not use genetic information to separate species (Tobias et al. 2010). Schodde and Mason (1999) describe morphological differences between the two forms as 'fine'. They assert that there are marked differences in territorial song but Higgins et al. (2001) state that further investigation is required; Christidis and Boles (2008) make no reference to vocal differences.

column8: Subspecies from Schodde and Mason (1999). Meliphaga albilineata (Sibley and Monroe 1990, 1993; Christidis and Boles 1994) was split into M. albilineata and M. fordiana by Christidis and Boles (2008) but this treatment is not followed because BirdLife International does not use genetic information to separate species (Tobias et al. 2010). Schodde and Mason (1999) describe morphological differences between the two forms as 'fine'. They assert that there are marked differences in territorial song but Higgins et al. (2001) state that further investigation is required; Christidis and Boles (2008) make no reference to vocal differences. Maintained within M.albilineata by Johnstone and Darnell (2015).
